value.value: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of (1->4)-alpha-glucans, compounds composed of glucose residues linked by (1->4)-alpha-D-glucosidic bonds.
Any process in which a spindle pole body is transported to, or maintained in, a specific location. A spindle pole body is a type of microtubule organizing center found in fungal cells.
The directed movement of a substance from one side of an epithelium to the other.
The directed movement of ammonium ions from one side of an epithelium to the other.
Catalysis of the reaction: nicotinamide riboside + H2O = nicotinamide + D-ribose.
Catalysis of the reaction: nicotinic acid riboside + H2O = nicotinic acid + D-ribose.
The chemical reactions and pathways involving any pyridine nucleoside, a nucleoside in which a pyridine base covalently bonded to a sugar, usually ribose.
The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of any pyridine nucleoside, a nucleoside in which a pyridine base covalently bonded to a sugar, usually ribose.
The chemical reactions and pathways involving vitamin D2, (3S,5Z,7E,22E)-9,10-secoergosta-5,7,10(19),22-tetraen-3-ol.
The chemical reactions and pathways involving vitamin D3, (3S,5Z,7E)-9,10-secocholesta-5,7,10(19)-trien-3-ol.
The chemical reactions and pathways involving vitamin D4, (3S,5Z,7E)-9,10-secoergosta-5,7,10(19)-trien-3-ol.

The chemical reactions and pathways involving vitamin D5, (1S,3Z)-3-[(2E)-2-[(1R,3aS,7aR)-1-[(1R,4S)-4-ethyl-1,5-dimethylhexyl]-7a-methyl-2,3,3a,5,6,7-hexahydro-1H-inden-4-ylidene]ethylidene]-4-methylene-1-cyclohexanol.
Catalysis of the hydroxylation of C-25 of any form of vitamin D.
Binding to a vitamin D response element (VDRE), a short sequence with dyad symmetry found in the promoters of some of the cellular immediate-early genes, regulated by serum.

A small, granular structure that is found in the extracellular matrix of cell of the secretory tapetal layer that surrounds developing pollen grains. Ubisch bodies have a sporopollenin coat, are attached to the peritapetal wall, and may play a role in pollen development.

label.value: protein modification by small protein removal

value.value: A protein modification process in which one or more covalently attached groups of a small protein, such as ubiquitin or a ubiquitin-like protein, are removed from a target protein.

label.value: protein modification by small protein conjugation or removal

value.value: A protein modification process in which one or more groups of a small protein, such as ubiquitin or a ubiquitin-like protein, are covalently attached to or removed from a target protein.

An actin filament bundle that consists of short filaments organized into bundles of uniform polarity, and is nucleated by formins. In fungal cells, myosin motors transport cargo along actin cables toward sites of polarized cell growth; actin cables may play a similar role in pollen tube growth.

The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form a formin-nucleated actin cable. A formin-nucleated actin cable is an actin filament bundle that consists of short filaments organized into bundles of uniform polarity, and is nucleated by formins.
Any cellular process that establishes the spatial arrangement of actin filament bundles within the cell.
An rRNA catabolic process that results in the targeted detection and degradation of aberrant rRNAs contained within translationally defective ribosomes, thereby acting as a quality-control system.

A protein complex that localizes to interphase centrosomes and to mitotic spindle tubules and regulates mitotic spindle assembly and centrosome integrity; in human, the complex consists of eight subunits, some of which are homologous to subunits of the Drosophila Augmin complex.
Binding to a high-density lipoprotein receptor.
The regrowth of a sensory epithelium following its loss or destruction.
The regrowth of lost or destroyed mechanosensory epithelia.

label.value: mechanoreceptor differentiation involved in mechanosensory epithelium regeneration

value.value: Differentiation of new mechanoreceptors to replace those lost or destroyed by injury.
The regrowth of a neuromast following its loss or destruction.

label.value: neuromast hair cell differentiation involved in neuromast regeneration

value.value: Differentiation of new neuromast sensory hair cells to replace those lost or destroyed by injury.
The regrowth of lost or destroyed inner ear sensory epithelia.

label.value: inner ear receptor cell differentiation involved in inner ear sensory epithelium regeneration

value.value: Differentiation of new inner ear sensory hair cells to replace those lost or destroyed by injury.
The expansion of a leukocyte population by cell division.
The expansion of a mast cell population by cell division.
Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of leukocyte proliferation.
Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of leukocyte proliferation.
Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of leukocyte proliferation.
Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of mast cell proliferation.

label.value: negative regulation of mast cell proliferation

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the rate or extent of mast cell proliferation.

label.value: positive regulation of mast cell proliferation

value.value: Any process that activates or increases the rate or extent of mast cell proliferation.

Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an interleukin-2 stimulus.

Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an interleukin-4 stimulus.

Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an interleukin-12 stimulus.

Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an interleukin-15 stimulus.

Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an interleukin-18 stimulus.
Catalysis of the reaction: hypoxanthine + NAD+ + H2O = xanthine + NADH + H+.
Catalysis of the reaction: hypoxanthine + H2O + O2 = xanthine + H2O2.
The invagination of the endosome membrane and resulting formation of a vesicle within the lumen of the endosome.
Catalysis of the reaction: S-adenosyl-L-methionine + rRNA = S-adenosyl-L-homocysteine + rRNA containing 2'-O-methylcytosine.
Binding to a preprotein, the unprocessed form of a protein destined to undergo co- or post-translational processing.
Binding to inositol 1,4,5 trisphosphate.

A tRNA aminoacylation process in which asparaginyl-tRNAAsn is formed by a tRNA-dependent two-step pathway. In the first step a non-discriminating aspartyl-tRNA synthetase generates the misacylated L-aspartyl-tRNAAsn species, and in the second step it is amidated to the correctly charged L-asparaginyl-tRNAAsn by the heterotrimeric aspartyl-tRNAAsn amidotransferase.
